[ProMED posts the 1st incidence of chronic wasting disease in a county or territory. Subsequent cases are not posted. It appears this may be the 1st case in Taylor County (WI) and in Limestone and Gillespie counties, both in Texas.

Chronic wasting disease (CWD) is a neurological, degenerative disease of parts of the brain.

Hunters will surely have new regulations to be aware of by the next hunting season. Some counties in Wisconsin are already familiar with CWD hunting regulations.

Generally, meat from CWD is not consumed by humans out of an abundance of caution.

The causative agent for CWD is a prion. Prions have been linked to bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or mad cow disease. Consequently, it is believed this prion disease could have similar negative consequences.

"Chronic wasting disease (CWD) is a fatal, neurological illness occurring in North American cervids (members of the deer family), including white-tailed deer, mule deer, elk, and moose. Since its discovery in 1967, CWD has spread geographically and increased in prevalence locally. CWD is contagious; it can be transmitted freely within and among cervid populations. No treatments or vaccines are currently available.

"Chronic wasting disease is of great concern to wildlife managers. It has been detected in at least 23 states, 2 Canadian provinces, and South Korea. CWD is not known to infect livestock or humans.

"CWD is transmitted directly through animal-to-animal contact, and indirectly through contact with objects or environments contaminated with infectious material (including saliva, urine, feces, and carcasses of CWD-infected animals)."
(https://www.usgs.gov/faqs/what-chronic-wasting-disease) - Mod.TG]
